rciesgeipqsszerswgbajqustitcsclgeatamifs length 6 140682 page 6793 Not to be confused with the Border Guard Forces. Border Guard Police Country Myanmar Branch Special Department of the Myanmar Police Force Type Border guard Role Border control Close-quarters combat Counterinsurgency Crowd control Force protection HUMINT Internal security Jungle warfare Law enforcement Mountain warfare Patrolling Raiding Reconnaissance Screening Security checkpoint Tracking Urban warfare Part of Myanmar Police Force Nickname(s) BGP Commanders Current commander Brig. Gen. Myint Toe[1] Insignia Emblem Military unit The Border Guard Police (Burmese: နယ်ခြားစောင့်ရဲတပ်ဖွဲ့; abbreviated BGP) are a department of Myanmar's Myanmar Police Force, specialising in border control, counterinsurgency, crowd control and security checkpoints in border areas and insurgent areas, gathering intelligence in local areas to counterinsurgency and counter perpetrators in border areas, internal security, law enforcement in border areas and insurgency areas, and protecting agency assets in risky areas. The BGP operate in northern Rakhine State and are especially active along the Bangladesh–Myanmar border, due to the ongoing exodus of Rohingya people fleeing sectarian violence in Myanmar.[2] In addition to border security, the BGP are also responsible for manning checkpoints and documenting the movement of Rohingyas within Rakhine State. Insurgents of the Arakan Rohingya Salvation Army have repeatedly attacked BGP posts along the Bangladesh–Myanmar border in revenge for the BGP's mistreatment of the Rohingya.[3][4][5][6] References[edit] ^ "Maungdaw Border Guard Police Chief Replaced". The Irrawaddy. 4 October 2017. Retrieved 22 November 2017. ^ Aziz, Abdul (September 25, 2017). "Myanmar reinforces barbed wire fence at border". Dhaka Tribune. Retrieved 22 November 2017. ^ Lone, Wa; Naing, Shoon (2017). "At least 71 killed in Myanmar as Rohingya insurgents stage major attack". Reuters. Retrieved 22 November 201